      <tr><td>500 Hz</td><td>2.0 ms</td><td>Competitive gaming (minimum)</td><td><span class="badge badge-blue">Good</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td>1000 Hz</td><td>1.0 ms</td><td>Standard gaming</td><td><span class="badge badge-purple">Great</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td>4000 Hz</td><td>0.25 ms</td><td>High-refresh-rate gaming</td><td><span class="badge badge-purple">Elite</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td>8000 Hz</td><td>0.125 ms</td><td>Esports professionals</td><td><span class="badge badge-purple">Pro</span></td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <h2 style="margin-top:2rem;">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq-list">
    <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">What polling rate does this tool support?</div><div class="faq-a">This tool uses a low-overhead architecture with requestAnimationFrame rendering and GPU-composited cursor movement. It can accurately measure polling rates from 125Hz all the way up to 8000Hz without dropping events.</div></div>
    <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">What is a good polling rate for gaming?</div><div class="faq-a">500Hz is the competitive minimum. 1000Hz is the standard for most gaming mice. Ultra-competitive players on high-refresh monitors prefer 4000Hz or 8000Hz.</div></div>
    <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Is higher polling rate always better?</div><div class="faq-a">Not necessarily. Above 4000Hz, CPU usage increases slightly. The benefit depends on your monitor refresh rate — a 4000Hz mouse on a 60Hz monitor provides no visible advantage.</div></div>
    <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Can I increase my mouse polling rate?</div><div class="faq-a">Yes, through manufacturer software — Logitech G HUB, Razer Synapse, or SteelSeries Engine — if your mouse hardware supports it. Not all mice can exceed 1000Hz.</div></div>
  </div>
